node.text: Fans of apple crisps and crumbles will love this warm dessert served with a scoop of vanilla ice cream slowly melting over top. This dessert is perfect for Rosh Hashanah since it brings together challah, apples, and honey—all symbols of luck in the New Year. node.text: We can all agree that few dishes are as elemental and versatile as hummus—the creamy chickpea-and-tahini purée is a plush landing pad for herbs, vegetables, and even meat. In our September issue, acclaimed Israel-born restauranteur @chefeinat shares her signature, light-as-air hummus recipe that's magic to make at home. Admony recommends using smaller dried chickpeas when making hummus. And she calls for soaking them overnight (no rushing) with 1/2 teaspoon baking soda. This softens the dried chickpeas and helps them to plump up before they are cooked. After the chickpeas are cooked, she drains and puts them in a bowl set in an ice bath to let them cool completely before processing. Get the full recipe in our September issue or at the link in bio. 📷: @quentinbaconphoto

node.text: Making your own granola is easy and the results are delicious—every morning. Our basic granola recipe is adaptable and you can use whatever nuts, seeds, or dried fruit you have on hand. Make it a couple of times and then start switching around the pairings to see what you like best. Trust us, there are no bad combinations in this winning formula. node.text: One easy way to keep your pantry organized? By adding as much dedicated storage as possible. Sure, shelves are great, but go the extra mile by adding baskets and canisters to stash specific items in, then give everything in your pantry it's own dedicated space. Rather than putting stickers on each container, designate zones (for oils, condiments, snacks) with bookplates. "They keep everything organized and add vintage charm," says @lornaaragon, our home editor. Using inexpensive crates, which allow for air flow, to store potatoes and onions extends their shelf-life, while putting your prettiest bowls to good use. Learn more in our September issue or at the link in bio. 📷: @ryanliebe

node.text: It’s not the end of summer pie season yet! In this delicious apricot pie, sweet coconut crumble offsets the tart apricot filling. The topping browns quickly because of the sugar in the coconut, so tent it with foil after 30 minutes to avoid burning. Get the recipe at the link in bio! 📷: @conpoulos_photographer

node.text: If you’re hosting your last summer gathering this Labor Day weekend, we’ve got a recipe that guests will love. While you could certainly grill your ribs, our recipe for Tuscan ribs puts the oven to good use. Three racks of baby back ribs marinate with olive oil, paprika, fennel seeds, sage, thyme, and rosemary. They slow-roast in the oven for two hours until the meat is fork-tender and releases its juicy flavor. Get the recipe at the link in bio! 📷: @ryanliebe

node.text: Consider this another great reason to go apple-picking this September—or a fun and unexpected twist to serve on Rosh Hashanah, as it's Jewish custom to eat apple slices dipped in honey to ensure the new year will be fruitful and sweet. Those two ingredients define this upside-down dessert from Martha, and it's the perfect treat to enjoy on a crisp fall evening. Check out more recipes from @marthastewart48’s upcoming book Fruit Desserts: 100+ Ways to Savor the Best of Every Season in our September issue, out on newsstands! 📷: @johnny_miller_
